******
[3]
Date: Thu 10 Sep 2015
Source: The Portugal News Online [edited]
http://theportugalnews.com/news/no-new-legionnaires-cases-in-greater-oporto-health-authorities/35875


Portugal's national health authorities said on Wednesday [9 Sep 2015] that there have been no new cases of Legionnaires' disease uncovered by the investigation currently underway into the outbreak.

At a news conference in the city [Oporto] on Monday [7 Sep 2015], the director-general of health, Francisco George, said that since the last week of July [2015] there had been 16 cases of Legionnaires' [disease] reported in the Greater Oporto region, 2 of them picked up abroad.

Of the 5 people who were in hospital on Wednesday afternoon, George told Lusa, all are doing well.

There is another patient in hospital in Lisbon with the same disease, but that case is not related with those in the north of the country, he said.

On Saturday [5 Sep 2015], Porto's Hotel Boa-Vista undertook a treatment of its internal water system on suspicion of contamination by the bacterium that causes Legionnaires' [disease]. Apart from one Swedish and one French citizen who stayed in the hotel and contracted the disease, there is one other person who also stayed there and is currently in hospital in Lisbon.

The last major outbreak of Legionnaires' [disease] in Portugal was in November 2014, when 12 people died and 375 were infected in Vila Franca de Xira, north of Lisbon. [See prior ProMED-mail posts for this 2014 outbreak in Vila Franca de Xira, Portugal.] The [2014] outbreak was brought under control in 2 weeks.

