[This Legionnaires' disease outbreak in Oporto, Portugal, was initially reported by ProMED-PORT in posts: Legionelose - Portugal (PO), casos confirmados, surto (?) 20150905.3625785 and Legionelose - Portugal (02) (PO), casos confirmados, surto (?), informações oficiais 20150907.3626549.

There are apparently at least 2 outbreaks of Legionnaires' disease in Oporto. One outbreak is affecting people who stayed at Oporto's Hotel Boa-Vista and involves 3 people: a citizen of France, a citizen of Sweden and an additional person currently hospitalized in Lisbon.

A 2nd outbreak involves 16 patients who reside in the Greater Metropolitan Area of Porto, 2 of whom are said to have acquired Legionnaires' disease abroad.

Genotyping of _Legionella_ isolates will help establish transmission pathways. The predominance of one genotype of _Legionella_ isolated from patient specimens will suggest transmission from a common source. Because _Legionella_ may be found in environmental samples without linkage to any cases of legionellosis, the actual causative infectious reservoir can be confirmed by matching the genotype of clinical and environmental isolates (see http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC86783/ and http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2730281/).

However, this is often difficult in legionellosis outbreaks, because the diagnosis is frequently made only on the basis of urinary _Legionella pneumophila_ serogroup 1 antigen testing or serology, rather than isolation of the organism from cultures of respiratory tract specimens [most Legionella colonies on specialized medium are detected within 3-5 days. - Mod.JW]. Consequently, clinical isolates are often not available for genotyping.

Porto, also known as Oporto in English, located in Northern Portugal, with a population of 1.4 million in 2011, is the 2nd-largest city in Portugal, after Lisbon (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Porto). - Mod.ML

A HealthMap of Porto, Portugal is at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3640216,8596]
